ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED-mail would appreciate more information about this cluster of cases.
The last of the 3 reports implies that the illness in this cluster was
botulism. This, however, is not likely to be the case as the incubation
period of foodborne botulism is usually 12-36 hours, substantially longer
than the 3 hours or less noted in this cluster. Furthermore, the cause of
death in botulism is respiratory failure related to neuromuscular
transmission block. Indeed, botulism, although sometimes beginning with
nausea and diarrhea, is basically a descending paralysis beginning with the
cranial nerves. No neurological symptoms appear to be described. Finally,
the fermenting of milk produces acid and _C. botulinum_ does not grow well
in a highly acid medium. One study, however, reported that milk, inoculated
with _C. botulinum_ spores, was found to contain botulinum toxin after
spoilage at 21 degrees C for 6 days (1). Fermentation of some foods,
however, can be associated with botulism. Examples include a variety of
fermented marine products including beaver tail (2), salmon roe (3), walrus
flipper (4), and fish (5). A concise review of dairy product post-harvest
protection is given by Stabel (6).
It may well be the case that the etiology of the cluster is an exogenous
toxin or poison that contaminated the fermented milk before, during or
after fermentation. The need for isolation for these cases is unclear.
1. Glass KA, Kaufman KM, Smith AL, et al. Toxin production by Clostridium
botulinum in pasteurized milk treated with carbon dioxide. J Food Prot
1999; 62: 872-6.
2. Shaffer N, Wainwright RB, Middaugh JP, Tauxe RV. Botulism among Alaska
natives. The role of changing food preparation and consumption practices.
West J Med 1990; 153: 390-3.
3. Public Health Agency of Canada. Two outbreaks of botulism associated
with fermented salmon roe - British Columbia, August 2001. Can Comm Dis Rep
2001; 28-06. <http://phac-aspc.gc.ca/publicat/ccdr-rmtc-02vol28/dr2806ea.html>
4. State of Alaska. Fatal botulism - fermented walrus flipper. State of
Alaska Epidemiology Bulletin, Bulletin 1, 1990.
<http://www.epi.hss.state.ak.us/bulletins/docs/b1990_01.htm>
5. Jensen T, Jacobsen D, von der Lippe E, Yndestad M. [Botulism after
intake of half-fermented fish] Tidsskr Nor Laegeforen. 1998; 118: 4377-67.
6. Stabel JR. Effective methods for postharvest intervention in dairy
processing. J Dairy Sci 2003; 86(E. Suppl): E10-E15. - Mod.LL]
